{
  "title": "Adjectives and adverbs",
  "body": [
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "Adjectives can either be placed before a noun or be joined to a noun by a verb. If placed before a noun, they come between the article and the noun. Examples:"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "table": [
        [
          "de",
          "mooie tuin",
          "the beautiful garden"
        ],
        [
          "een",
          "mooie tuin",
          " a beautiful garden"
        ],
        [
          "mooie",
          "tuin",
          "beautiful garden"
        ],
        [
          "de",
          "mooie tuinen",
          " the beautiful gardens"
        ],
        [
          "-",
          "mooie tuinen",
          " beautiful gardens"
        ],
        [
          "het",
          "mooie boek",
          " the beautiful book"
        ],
        [
          "een",
          "mooi boek",
          " a beautiful book"
        ],
        [
          "mooi",
          "boek",
          "beautiful book"
        ],
        [
          "de",
          "mooie boeken",
          "the beautiful books"
        ],
        [
          "-",
          "mooie boeken",
          " beautiful books"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "From the above you can see that an adjective before a noun always has the ending -e, except if it precedes a singular het-noun used with een1. This also applies if there is no article at all or if een is replaced by one of the following words:"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "table": [
        [
          "geen",
          "no, not a"
        ],
        [
          "zo'n",
          "such a"
        ],
        [
          "elk",
          "every"
        ],
        [
          "welk",
          "which (Both the interrogative and the (formal) relative pronoun)"
        ],
        [
          "veel",
          "much (The word veel followed by a singular noun can only denote uncountable concepts)"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "Therefore, to make the correct form of the adjective it is important to know whether a noun is a de-noun or an het-noun."
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "table": [
        [
          "een mooi boek (het boek!)",
          "a beautiful book"
        ],
        [
          "geen mooi boek",
          "no beautiful book"
        ],
        [
          "zo'n mooi boek",
          "such a beautiful book"
        ],
        [
          "elk mooi boek",
          "every beautiful book"
        ],
        [
          "welk mooi boek(?)",
          "which beautiful book(?)"
        ],
        [
          "veel oud brood (het brood!)",
          "much stale bread"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "Compare:"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "table": [
        [
          "een leuke dag (de dag!)",
          "a pleasant day"
        ],
        [
          "geen leuke dag",
          "not a pleasant day"
        ],
        [
          "zo'n leuke dag",
          "such a pleasant day"
        ],
        [
          "elke leuke dag",
          "every pleasant day"
        ],
        [
          "welke leuke dag(?)",
          "which pleasant day(?)"
        ],
        [
          "(veel leuke dagen ",
          "many pleasant days)"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "Like the spelling of the nouns, for reasons of correct pronunciation the spelling of an adjective may change slightly when an ending is added. Examples:"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "table": [
        [
          "droog/droge",
          "een droge dag - a dry day"
        ],
        [
          "nat/natte",
          "een natte dag - a wet day"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "Adjectives that are joined to a noun by a verb have no ending:"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "table": [
        [
          "De tuin is mooi.",
          "The garden is beautiful."
        ],
        [
          "De tuinen zijn mooi.",
          "The gardens are b..."
        ],
        [
          "Het boek blijft mooi.",
          "The book remains b..."
        ],
        [
          "De boeken blijven mooi.",
          "The books remain beautiful."
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "Adjectives ending in -en always remain unchanged:"
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "(gevonden* - Past participles of verbs are often used as adjectives. The past participles of many strong verbs end in -en, so they also remain unchanged when used as adjectives.)"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "table": [
        [
          "gevonden voorwerpen",
          "lost property (litterally: found objects)"
        ],
        [
          "een gebakken ei",
          "a fried egg"
        ],
        [
          "een open deur",
          "an open door"
        ],
        [
          "een dronken zeeman",
          "a drunken sailor"
        ],
        [
          "onze eigen bagage",
          "our own luggage"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "A small group of other adjectives also remain unchanged:"
    },
    {
      "type": "b",
      "text": "- adjectives ending in -a or in -schwa"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "table": [
        [
          "prima",
          " excellent"
        ],
        [
          "een prima idee",
          "an excellent idea"
        ],
        [
          "oranje",
          "orange"
        ],
        [
          "een oranje pet",
          "an orange cap"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "b",
      "text": "'modern materials' like:"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "table": [
        [
          "plastic",
          "(made of) plastic"
        ],
        [
          "een plastic zakje",
          "a (small) plastic bag"
        ],
        [
          "aluminium",
          "(made of) aluminium"
        ],
        [
          "een aluminium ladder",
          "an aluminium ladder"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "Comparatives and Comparatives are usually made by adding -er to the adjective, superlatives superlatives are made by adding -st."
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "table": [
        [
          "klein, kleiner, kleinst",
          "all, smaller etc."
        ],
        [
          "leuk, leuker, leukst",
          "nice etc."
        ],
        [
          "mooi, mooier, mooist",
          "beautiful etc."
        ],
        [
          "kort, korter, kortst",
          "short etc."
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "In comparatives of adjectives ending in -r, a -d is added:"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "table": [
        [
          "duur, duurder, duurst",
          "expensive etc."
        ],
        [
          "zwaar, zwaarder, zwaarst",
          "heavy etc."
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "A small group of comparatives and superlatives is irregular:"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "table": [
        [
          "goed, beter, best",
          " good, better, best"
        ],
        [
          "graag, liever, liefst",
          "gladly, rather, for preference - In English these concepts are expressed in a different way"
        ],
        [
          "veel, meer, meest",
          "many/much, more, most"
        ],
        [
          "weinig, minder, minst ",
          "little, less, least"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "When comparing two specimens, in Dutch the superlative is used:"
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "(I have two daughters.) De oudste is 15 en de jongste is 12 - The elder (litterally: eldest) is 15 and the younger (litterally: youngest) is 12."
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "Iets, niets When combined with iets 'something' or niets 'nothing' an adjective"
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "+adjective takes s for an ending:"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "table": [
        [
          "iets moois",
          "something beautiful"
        ],
        [
          "iets raars",
          "something strange"
        ],
        [
          "niets belangrijks",
          "nothing important"
        ],
        [
          "niets nieuws",
          "nothing new"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "This does not apply to adjectives ending in s, for a Dutch word never ends in two identical consonants:"
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "iets vies - something dirty."
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "Adverbs Adjectives can be used as adverbs, too. There is no special adverbial (bijwoorden) form of the adjectives. Adverbs do not get an ending."
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "An exception is the adverb heel 'very', which in spoken language often behaves like an adjective: een hele hoge toren - a very high tower."
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "Examples:"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "table": [
        [
          "een fraai versierde schotel",
          "a finely garnished dish"
        ],
        [
          "een mooi gedekte tafel",
          "a beautifully set table"
        ],
        [
          "een zwaar opgemaakte dame",
          "a heavily painted lady"
        ],
        [
          "Ze hebben goed gewerkt",
          "They have worked well"
        ]
      ]
    }
  ]
}